div.p:
But to leaue the purſute of theſe fugitiues, & to come neerer to our ſelues; if this muſt bee done to theſe drie barren trees Luke 23.32., though they want not leaues to couer their nakednes, Math. 21.19. thogh
they haue a name and place within the walls of Gods houſe, Eſay 56.5. what profiteth it them to reſt in an outward profeſſion, ſhew of godlines, & to want the inward power, and life thereof? to be painted Sepulchres, beautifull without, loathſome within Math. 23 27., foris Catones, intus Nerones, outwardly as graue as Cato, inwardly as wilde as Nero: and as Saint Auſten ſpeaketh, in ſuperficie boni, in alto mali; in the outſide good, in the inſide euil: and to haue our fruit like to the Apple of Sodome, which Solinus. in the outſide hath a ſhew of ripeneſſe, but in the inſide ſmoaky duſt, ſo that vpon the leaſt touch it ſendeth out ſmoke, and goeth away in a flying duſt. Shall the wolfe euer be ſet on the right hand, becauſe hee commeth ſometimes in ſheepes cloathing? Math. 7.19. Shall not Sathan fall from Heauen like lightning, Luke 10.18. though heere hee often transforme himſelfe into an Angell of light? 2. Cor. 11.14. Shall not the fiue fooliſh Virgins, that brought with them the lamps of an outward profeſſion onely, and wanted the oyle of grace, bee ſhut out of the Kingdome? Math. 25.10. Could Ahab eſcape the ſtroake of the arrow, though hee were diſguiſed in his habite? 1. King. 22.34. And ſhall men, though they ſweare vaine, falſe oathes, commit murther, adultery and ſuch like wickedneſſe, be deliuered if they come and ſtand before God in his houſe? Ier. 7.9.10. Aſſuredly ſuch halting betweene God and world, will make vs pendere inter coelum & terram, hang betweene heauen and earth (as Eraſmus was painted) yea perdere coelum & terram, looſe both heauen & earth;
the world hating vs, becauſe wee are Chriſtians ſo much as in appearance, God hating vs double, becauſe wee are Chriſtians but in appearance.
